9. Interview Preparation: Whiteboard Ready

Core Variables (Define Instantly)

Variable Symbol Physical Significance
Packing Fraction \phi Solid‑like (\phi > \phi_c) vs. fluid‑like
Coordination Number Z Average contacts; v_p \propto Z^{1/3}
Stokes Number \text{St} = \tau_p / \tau_f Particle inertia vs. granular "viscosity"
Granular Temperature T_{gr} = \langle \delta v^2 \rangle Kinetic energy of fluctuations
Hamaker Constant A_H van der Waals attraction magnitude

Essential Equations (Derive on Demand)

I. Effective Modulus (Model A)

C_{ijkl}^{\text{eff}} = \frac{1}{V} \sum_{\text{contacts}} \left( k_n n_i n_j n_k n_l + k_t (t_i n_j t_k n_l + \cdots) \right)

II. Sintered Adhesion Force (Model B)

F_{\text{adh}} = \frac{A_H R}{12 D_0^2} + \pi r_n^2 \sigma_{\text{ice}}

III. Granular Radiation Force (Model C)

\mathbf{F}_{\text{rad}} = V_p \nabla \langle E \rangle \, \beta(\phi, \text{St})

IV. Langevin Equation (Stochastic Dynamics)

m\ddot{\mathbf{x}} = \mathbf{F}_{\text{contact}} - \gamma \dot{\mathbf{x}} + \boldsymbol{\xi}(t), \quad \langle \xi_i(t) \xi_j(t') \rangle = 2\gamma k_B T_{gr} \delta_{ij} \delta(t-t')

V. Beta Scaling Hypothesis

\beta(\phi, \text{St}) = \beta_0 \left(1 - \frac{\phi}{\phi_c}\right)^\alpha \exp\left(-\frac{\text{St}_0}{\text{St}}\right)

Stress Test Answers

Q: "Why does sound speed increase with confining pressure?"

A: "Hertzian contact theory gives k_n \propto F_n^{1/3}. Higher pressure increases contact area and stiffness. Through homogenization, C^{\text{eff}} \propto Z k_n, so wave speed v_p = \sqrt{C^{\text{eff}}/\rho_b} increases as P^{1/6}."

Q: "How does vacuum change acoustic radiation force compared to air?"

A: "In air, force comes from fluid‑structure interaction—scattering of pressure waves in the pore fluid. In vacuum, the pore fluid is absent. Momentum transfers purely through grain contacts. The medium itself becomes the 'fluid,' requiring a new theory where the effective properties come from contact mechanics, not fluid compressibility."

Q: "What's the physical meaning of granular temperature?"

A: "It's the kinetic energy density of fluctuating grain motions—analogous to thermal temperature in molecular gases. In vibrating beds, acoustic energy pumps energy into these fluctuations, reducing effective friction and enabling fluidization. We measure it via high‑speed tracking of grain velocity fluctuations."

Q: "How do you validate a stochastic model?"

A: "We don't validate single trajectories—we validate the distribution. 4D tomography gives us the experimental probability density W_{\text{exp}}(\mathbf{x}, t). We compare to the Fokker‑Planck solution W_{\text{theory}}(\mathbf{x}, t) using Kolmogorov‑Smirnov statistics. If the distributions match, the stochastic dynamics are correct."

